{DIALOGUE}: It's all right, son.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all right.
{DIALOGUE}: Salazar is here.
{DIALOGUE}: You're among gentlemen, now.
{DIALOGUE}: This shameful treatment will stop immediately.
{META_DATA}: (calling out)
{DIALOGUE}: Guard!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A GUARD appears in the doorway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco is spooked.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: I want to know who is responsible for this treatment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUARD
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: We aren't barbarians.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUARD
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Bring this man a change of good clothes.
{DIALOGUE}: Has he eaten?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{META_DATA}: (to Francisco)
{DIALOGUE}: You will dine with me from now on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco moves closer to Salazar already feeling safe in his presence.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. COURTHOUSE, SAN DIEGO - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A packed courthouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carl is at the defense table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He doesn't look at Helena who sits in the gallery next to Arnie Metzger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The PROSECUTOR is finishing his argument --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROSECUTOR
{DIALOGUE}: This is a man who heads a large criminal organization with international contacts we can only begin to understand.
{DIALOGUE}: Our case against him is very strong.
{DIALOGUE}: He is not a flight risk.
{DIALOGUE}: His flight is assured.
{DIALOGUE}: The people ask that your honor denies bail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The prosecutor sits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carl's defense lawyer, MICHAEL ADLER, from the Georgetown party, stands and speaks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADLER
{DIALOGUE}: My client is no more a flight risk than your Honor or the able prosecutor.
{DIALOGUE}: He is a pillar of his community, a family man with a wife and child in La Jolla, the community where he has made his home for over twenty years.
{DIALOGUE}: As our defense will quickly show, my client is guilty of nothing more than being a handy target for an admitted criminal.
{DIALOGUE}: Therefore we ask that you release Carl Ayala on his own recognizance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Adler sits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The JUDGE makes a quick decision.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna deny bail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The judge SLAMS his gavel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd is on its feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carl tries to get a glimpse of Helena.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They make eye contact.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reporters from the press gallery are yelling for Helena.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Arnie ushers her away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COURTHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Adler, Arnie, and Helena push through a crowd toward her car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are several reporters there who ask questions --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Ayala, were you aware your husband is the largest cocaine smuggler in America?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADLER
{DIALOGUE}: Alleged, people, alleged.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena gets into her car and slams the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Adler faces the reporters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER #2
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Ayala is it true your husband has ordered a hit on Eduardo Ruiz?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Adler is in a role he relishes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena drives away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We move up to Gordon, who is watching from the hotel window across the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He speaks into a walkie-talkie, and a car down below pulls out to follow Helena.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADLER
{DIALOGUE}: Carl Ayala sits on the board of the Children's Hospital.
{DIALOGUE}: He is heavily involved with Adult Literacy.
{DIALOGUE}: He has a small boy and another child on the way.
{DIALOGUE}: If you spread this kind of innuendo, you can expect legal recourse.
{DIALOGUE}: Are we clear on this point?
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GOVERNMENT BUILDING - EARLY MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The marble government corridors are empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one is in yet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One office has lights on.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. A.D.A. KELLY'S OFFICE - EARLY MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert Wakefield talks with an Assistant District Attorney, DAN KELLY, 40's.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: I appreciate you coming in so early.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: Judge Wakefield, it's an honor to handle it for you.
{DIALOGUE}: Consider it gone away.
{DIALOGUE}: She's a minor; it probably would've expunged on her 18th birthday anyway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: Still, this was a sensitive issue for me and I wanted to thank you personally.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: Like I said, open container, P.I., Misdemeanor possession.
{DIALOGUE}: Easy to make it disappear.
{DIALOGUE}: For you, poof, it's gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A.D.A. Kelly thinks a moment, then tries for tact.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: One thing bothers me... That kid they dropped off had coke and heroin in him.
{DIALOGUE}: Serious amounts.
{DIALOGUE}: He's lucky he lived.
{DIALOGUE}: So I gotta ask: what's your daughter on?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know what you mean.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, did you ask her?
{DIALOGUE}: What kind of drugs has she tried?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert is silent for a beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: I don't really know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: Is she in any kind of therapy... professional help?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: No, of course not.
{DIALOGUE}: She's one of the top students at her school.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A.D.A. KELLY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I hope it stays that way.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ROBERT'S CAR - EARLY MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert in his car, thinking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The streets are empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He picks up the cell phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{META_DATA}: (into phone)
{DIALOGUE}: It's Robert.
{DIALOGUE}: Wipe your schedule clean for the next three days.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm tired of talking to experts who never set foot outside the beltway.
{DIALOGUE}: It's time to see the front lines.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CAROLINE WAKEFIELD'S BATHROOM - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caroline sits on the toilet in her private bathroom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's not going to the bathroom, it's a seat and she's wearing her pajamas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's reading a magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The exhaust fan is on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are pictures of her and her friends on the walls: goofy pictures from camp, from school, a collage she's made with cutouts from magazine pictures and copy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the sink next to her is a little square of well-charred aluminum foil; she's done many hits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She leans over and picks up a small piece of crack cocaine from a small pile in her soap dish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She drops it on a clean place on the foil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She picks up a lighter and the tube of a ball point pen she's turned into a straw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She heats the bottom of the foil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crack "crackles."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She chases the smoke across the foil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A huge hit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She leans her head back, her eyes roll back, she tries to focus on the magazine, on anything, she stares up at the ceiling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She holds it as long as she can then blows it toward the exhaust fan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caroline looks at her watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's 7:20.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stands suddenly, unsteadily.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks at herself in the mirror.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's really high and indecisive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks around wildly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sees the shower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She turns it on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She drops her pajamas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She goes back to the foil and hits another piece of the rock, taking another really big hit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She crushes the foil and flushes it down the toilet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hops in the shower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN THE SHOWER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The water streams over her face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a long beat she finally exhales the smoke of the hit through the water and steam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's in ecstacy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's almost time to leave for school.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. LA JOLLA PLAYGROUND - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena reads a book, Madame Bovary by Gustave Flaubert, and keeps an eye on David, who is playing on the monkey bars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACROSS THE ROAD at a careful distance is the ubiquitous telephone repair van.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the roof a parabolic mike swivels around.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TELEPHONE REPAIR VAN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Castro and Gordon watch Helena via a small surveillance monitor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: You should see little Montel play.
{DIALOGUE}: Little Montel is the next Maradona.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: Maradona is a cokehead.
{DIALOGUE}: Hand of God, my ass.
{DIALOGUE}: We're wasting our time here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: He won.
{DIALOGUE}: He was a winner.
{DIALOGUE}: That bothers you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: Winners don't do coke.
{DIALOGUE}: Or haven't you been reading the bumper stickers?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon looks at the monitor --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: What do we have here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ON THE MONITOR:
{DIALOGUE}: David kicking a soccer ball with an older strange man, TIGRILLO, Latino, 40's, fit and tough looking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man is very good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He juggles the ball and bounces it off his head and David follows him away from the center of the playground.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PLAYGROUND - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena notices David moving away while playing with the man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She follows, then begins to jog after them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: David, come back here this minute.
{DIALOGUE}: David!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she closes distance the man stops juggling the ball and abruptly picks up David and begins swinging him around by his arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: David is having fun as Helena approaches.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: David --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DAVID
{DIALOGUE}: We're playing!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The strange man swings David up so that he's under his arm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, this is fun.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: Please put down my son.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man holds David.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Shouldn't let your kid wander off with strangers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: That's a valuable lesson.
{DIALOGUE}: David, come on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The strange man holds David tighter so that he's no longer having fun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins to wriggle --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Ayala --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This gets her attention --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Your husband owes a lot of money.
{DIALOGUE}: Enough that snapping this kid's neck wouldn't nearly cover it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: David begins to cry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena looks around wildly for help.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: You better come up with it in a hurry or your kid is going to disappear, and he won't turn up until the evening news.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He drops David who runs to his mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: You get exactly one warning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The strange man moves away across the field.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STRANGE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: The first payment is three million dollars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He continues walking away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TELEPHONE REPAIR VAN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon and Castro stare with rapt attention.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: Are you getting this on tape?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: I love my job.
{DIALOGUE}: I love it.
{DIALOGUE}: The next time I'm having a bad day you gotta remind me of right now and I'll get over it.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BARRACKS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Javier and Manolo stand guard outside the front door of the dining hall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Javi smokes a cigarette.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MANOLO
{DIALOGUE}: A group of us are going out tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: Who?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MANOLO
{DIALOGUE}: Guzman, Tomas, Esteban --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: Your new friends.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MANOLO
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: It should be fun.
{DIALOGUE}: You wanna come?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: Not this time.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DINING HALL - BARRACKS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco and Salazar eat at a beautifully set table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are waited on by military officers who serve perfect flan at the end of the meal.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANCISCO
{DIALOGUE}: In my home I have B&W speakers.
{DIALOGUE}: I recently purchased a compact disc burner.
{DIALOGUE}: I can make my own cd's, with whatever music I like, as if I bought them at the store, only I don't have to pay these crazy prices.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: We have much in common.
{DIALOGUE}: We both attended school in the United States, and both of our fathers are engineers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANCISCO
{DIALOGUE}: I got into stereo equipment when I was a kid.
{DIALOGUE}: Some people don't notice the difference but it is very important to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Of course it is.
{DIALOGUE}: Have some more wine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A soldier pours another glass of red for Francisco.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Now, Francisco, my friend... I must know where these men are who killed my captains.
{DIALOGUE}: Not where they were last week, but where they are today, and better still, tomorrow.
{DIALOGUE}: You are clever.
{DIALOGUE}: You can predict where they will be, can't you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco begins to weep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Salazar slides a pad of paper toward Francisco who slowly begins writing.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TIJUANA NEIGHBORHOOD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Manolo and Javier pound on the front door of an apartment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAN opens the door and they grab him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TIJUANA STREETS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAN walks down the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two SUV's pull up in front of him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts to run.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Salazar's men jump out and chase him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco is in the backseat of one of the SUV's, watching.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TIJUANA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An SUV pulls up to a curb.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SUV - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Javier and Manolo and Francisco sit in the SUV.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Francisco is weeping.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANCISCO
{DIALOGUE}: I can't go home.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to go.
{DIALOGUE}: Please don't make me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks beseechingly at them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: It's not our decision.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANCISCO
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be killed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: Stop complaining.
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody knows what you've been up to.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They push him out of the SUV.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAN DIEGO JAIL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Castro and Gordon sit with Eduardo Ruiz in a conference room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are recording his statements.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: Carlos, I mean Carl, started out in the family connection business: real estate in Tijuana, fishing boats out of Ensenada, hydroponic raspberries.
{DIALOGUE}: He met up with the Obregon brothers of the Tijuana Cartel who were interested in two things: entering society and using his fishing boats.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: So you pay off our customs officials?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: In Mexico law enforcement is an entrepreneurial activity, this is not so true for the USA.
{META_DATA}: (condescending)
{DIALOGUE}: Using regression analysis we made a study of the customs lanes at the border and calculated the odds of a search.
{DIALOGUE}: The odds are not high, and we found variables that reduce the odds.
{DIALOGUE}: We hire drivers with nothing to lose.
{DIALOGUE}: Then we throw a lot of product at the problem.
{DIALOGUE}: Some get stopped.
{DIALOGUE}: Enough get through.
{DIALOGUE}: It's not difficult.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: You'd think he wasn't sitting here facing life in prison.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: This has worked for years and it will continue to work for years.
{DIALOGUE}: NAFTA makes everything more difficult for you.
{DIALOGUE}: The border is disappearing.
{META_DATA}: (pointing at them)
{DIALOGUE}: You people are like those Japanese soldiers left behind on deserted islands who think that World War II is still going on.
{META_DATA}: (with total disdain)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me be the first to tell you, your government surrendered this war a long time ago.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{META_DATA}: (to Castro)
{DIALOGUE}: This attitude's not gonna help him any, is it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: I got greedy.
{DIALOGUE}: I decided to bring a little in on my own and somebody tipped you off.
{DIALOGUE}: That was my mistake.
{DIALOGUE}: Carl would never be so stupid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: He hired you.
{DIALOGUE}: That was a mistake.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: Carl and I were friends from childhood.
{DIALOGUE}: He was loyal, that's not a mistake.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TIJUANA - SAN DIEGO BORDER CROSSING - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Car after car, an unending multi-lane stream of vehicles moving into the U.S. Any of these cars could be carrying drugs.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CUSTOMS CONTROL BOOTH - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On an elevated walkway, this booth commands a view of everything.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert and Sheridan listen to an OFFICIAL give the spiel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OFFICIAL
{DIALOGUE}: The busiest land border crossing in the world.
{DIALOGUE}: Over forty-one thousand vehicles per day, twenty-two thousand pedestrians on foot.
{DIALOGUE}: I think we do a pretty good job but we know a lot of drugs are still getting through.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: Any idea how much?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OFFICIAL
{DIALOGUE}: I've read official estimates but I wouldn't bet my house on them.
{DIALOGUE}: I've heard the entire cocaine supply for the United States can fit into four tractor-trailers.
{META_DATA}: (gestures to the traffic)
{DIALOGUE}: At least a half-dozen of those cars right out there are carrying a load of dope, with drivers employed by people who don't give a damn if they're caught or not.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: What do you look for?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OFFICIAL
{DIALOGUE}: We ask questions and measure the answers.
{DIALOGUE}: When something doesn't ring true, a fact that doesn't make sense, a slight hesitation, then it's off to secondary for a closer look.
{DIALOGUE}: Before NAFTA we had about 1.9 million trucks a year.
{DIALOGUE}: Now it's almost double.
{DIALOGUE}: Pretty soon there'll be Mexican truck companies that will have as much freedom in crossing the border as American truck companies.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: Any way we can do it better?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OFFICIAL
{DIALOGUE}: Sure.
{DIALOGUE}: More money in intelligence on their side of the border.
{DIALOGUE}: So we have a better idea who we're looking for.
{DIALOGUE}: More dogs.
{DIALOGUE}: More people.
{DIALOGUE}: Supposed to be getting some giant x- ray machines to run the trucks through.
{DIALOGUE}: Outside of martial law that's about the best you're gonna do.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: But, I should tell you, there are two things that really have us on edge right now.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: In the last six months seizures have tripled, even though we're pulling over the same number of cars.
{DIALOGUE}: What does that tell you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: That triple the amount of stuff is going through.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OFFICIAL
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: But, that's not the biggest problem.
{DIALOGUE}: One of our Intel officers picked up information from DEA that traffickers have come up with a process, a chemical process, to turn coke into something else.
{DIALOGUE}: It doesn't smell like coke.
{DIALOGUE}: It doesn't look like coke.
{DIALOGUE}: And what's worse, it doesn't react to field test.
{DIALOGUE}: It could be anything.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe it's already happening.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, how would we know?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert looks out at the border activity.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's anarchy.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AYALA STUDY - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena is on the floor surrounded by papers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's made piles of certain things: articles of incorporation, shipping/transfer documentation, bank statements, credit card statements.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She holds a telephone to her ear --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{META_DATA}: (to phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, hi Jenny, account number 4168 2245 3173... I need a cash advance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena walks into her kitchen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's serene in the afternoon light.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She fixes ice-cold lemonade and fills two plastic cups.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: What's the largest amount I can get?
{META_DATA}: (listens)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, I guess that'll have to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena hangs up the phone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes the two cups of lemonade to the front door and steps outside.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AYALA HOME - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena carries the cups down the driveway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She presses a button and the gates swing open.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TELEPHONE REPAIR VAN - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon and Castro listen to their headsets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VOICE (O.S.)
{META_DATA}: (over their headsets)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: She's coming out.
{DIALOGUE}: She's leaving her property.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, she seems to be heading for the van!
{DIALOGUE}: She is approaching the van!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Castro and Gordon looks at each other.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: What do we do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a KNOCKING at the door of the van.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: What do you think she wants?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: She's your girlfriend.
{DIALOGUE}: Open it, talk about your kids.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon opens the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena is standing there with the lemonade.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: I so hope I didn't startle you.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you might like some cold lemonade.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: Uh... Thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands the cups to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena gathers herself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: I know this is a difficult situation and you're only doing your jobs.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't bear you any ill-will, but I do have a small favor to ask.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: You want to ask us a favor?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: A man threatened my children.
{DIALOGUE}: These charges have attracted a lot of attention and it seems to be bringing all the nut-jobs out of the nut jar.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Would you keep an eye out for anything out of the ordinary.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know what else to do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: Of course, we will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HELENA
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They shut the door to the van and sit for a moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: It's probably poisoned.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon takes a big sip of his.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: It's good.
{DIALOGUE}: Not too sweet.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TIJUANA STREET - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is a questionable neighborhood pushed up against the edge of poverty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anna hurries across the street.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. JAVI'S APARTMENT BUILDING - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anna walks up the stairs of a rundown building.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She passes two PROSTITUTES loitering in the stairwell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She knocks on a door and Javi, half-dressed for work, answers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's surprised to see her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAVIER
{DIALOGUE}: Anna.
{DIALOGUE}: What's wrong?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want?
