{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SERENITY OAKS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A peaceful wooded campus with a unobtrusive sign reading, "Serenity Oaks Treatment Facility."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MEETING ROOM - SERENITY OAKS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are sayings on the wall: "Easy Does It;" "Let Go and Let God;" "Turn it over;" "One Day at a Time..." "H.A.L.T. -- Hungry?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Angry?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lonely?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tired?"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caroline, wearing a thick, woolly sweater, and the other PATIENTS sit around on beat-up couches and chairs in a loose circle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a mixed BUNCH: trucker meth-head, rocker dope- fiend, yuppie crack-head, fat, thin, rich, middle-class, and all white.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caroline is the youngest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MARTY, 40's, an overweight alcoholic, finishes his "share."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTY
{DIALOGUE}: So it was my birthday an my ex-wife was getting remarried and I was in some church basement telling a bunch of strangers how it was a good day because I didn't have to eat out of a dumpster.
{DIALOGUE}: That was enough to send me out on big one.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I've been thinking a lot about the first step: that I came to believe I was powerless over alcohol and that my life had become unmanageable.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: See my disease tells me I don't have a disease.
{DIALOGUE}: That I'm fine.
{DIALOGUE}: That it's my birthday and I can have one little drink, then one little line, then one little Valium, then two more fat lines, then two more 10 mil Valium... Six months later I wake up in a sober living house in Philly.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'm from Dallas, people.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: It's a disease -- an allergy of the body and an obsession of the mind.
{DIALOGUE}: I know that now.
{DIALOGUE}: So my name's Marty and today I'm a grateful recovering alcoholic who didn't eat out of a dumpster.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Marty looks to Caroline who didn't relate to one word he said.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAROLINE
{META_DATA}: (slowly, very nervous)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Caroline.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not sure I'm an alcoholic.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I mean I don't really like to drink.
{DIALOGUE}: For someone my age it's so much easier to get drugs than beer.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know, this is really weird and I'm really nervous...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: People in the room nod encouragingly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAROLINE
{DIALOGUE}: I guess I'm angry.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean I think I'm really angry about a lot of stuff, but I don't know what exactly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She blushes, and stares out the window.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AYALA LIVING ROOM - AFTERNOON
