{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her eyes are wide open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She has had a thought --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She climbs out of bed and quickly puts on a robe.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPSTAIRS HALLWAY - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena walks quickly and quietly down the hallway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She passes David's room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She opens a door at the end of the hall --
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CARL'S PRIVATE STUDY - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena enters the room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hits a desk lamp and we're in a very comfortable and masculine upstairs study: bookshelves holding hundreds of art books; comfortable chairs; MacIntosh stereo; discreet flatscreen HD TV.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Helena stares at a painting on one of the bookshelves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is "Boy with a Hoop," a small portrait by Rafael Colonel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She goes to it and looks from different angles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She reaches out and jiggles the oil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nothing happens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks behind the painting at the backing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She notices that one corner is not glued down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She picks up a letter opener and pries the paper back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An envelope slips out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside the envelope: neat, thin strips of paper dense with information in a miniscule type and a magnetic key card.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HELICOPTER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert and Sheridan ride in the back of the chopper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Each looks out his own window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A newspaper on the seat between them shows a front page photo of General Salazar, exultant, and the headline reads in Spanish, "Salazar Named Chief of Anti-Narcotics Operations."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MEXICO CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Establishing shot of a military helicopter landing on the roof of an office building in downtown Mexico City.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HEADQUARTERS, FEADS, - MEXICO CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert Wakefield and General Salazar stroll through the new headquarters where boxes are still being unpacked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Javier and Sheridan trail along behind them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: I recruited the best men in Mexico for my task force and put them through a rigorous screening process.
{DIALOGUE}: Not only physical, but also psychological.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: I'd like to bring you up to Washington, walk you around our side of things, and share some of the information we've been able to develop on your cartels.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: That would be very helpful to me.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Also, I received the offer from DEA and the FBI to train some of my men at Quantico.
{DIALOGUE}: I think this will be extremely useful, a good way for us to absorb some of your methods.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SALAZAR'S I.N.C.D. OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The office hasn't been decorated yet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: I've been too busy to completely settle in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Salazar proffers a chair and they sit next to each other like Brezhnev and Nixon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PHOTOGRAPHERS begin SNAPPING pictures.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a few moments, Salazar waves them away, and they lower their cameras and leave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: You've been making very good progress against the Tijuana cartel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, I am confident that Juan Obregon will be taken into custody before the end of the year.
{DIALOGUE}: But, you must understand that it is very difficult because of corruption in the police force.
{DIALOGUE}: We get a tip that he is one place, then we get there and he is already gone, having been warned by someone on our side.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: Hopefully the exchange of training methods and information between our countries will help with this problem.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, I hope so as well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: Let me ask you a related question.
{DIALOGUE}: We've talked about the supply side, but what about demand?
{DIALOGUE}: What is your policy for treating addiction?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SALAZAR
{DIALOGUE}: Addicts treat themselves... they overdose and then there's one less to worry about.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert cannot respond.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SERENITY OAKS - WALKWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caroline ambles alone down a walkway at the treatment facility.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks through the trees that surround facility and notices cars going by.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LOW-RENT HOTEL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon and another DEA AGENT escort Ruiz up the stairs of a large, older hotel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: This is ridiculous.
{DIALOGUE}: Why is there no elevator?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: When the DEA gets into the narcotics business, then we'll stay at the Four Seasons.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They walk down a hotel hallway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two more AGENTS stand outside Room 407.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon opens the door and they enter.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SUITE OF CHEAP HOTEL ROOMS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are more AGENTS inside and old food and coffee containers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon gives Ruiz a tour.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are several rooms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bored Castro sits at a table staring at a Scrabble board.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASTRO
{DIALOGUE}: Eddie, how you like your new home?
{DIALOGUE}: I hope you hate it as much as I do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ruiz looks around with disgust.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's accustomed to finer places.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes to a window and looks out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RUIZ'S POV: of the Federal Court building not far away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUIZ
{DIALOGUE}: This is not what my lawyers negotiated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon pours himself a cup of coffee.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GORDON
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck your lawyers.
{DIALOGUE}: You aren't getting any cappuccino or Biscotti either.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FEDERAL COURTHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A packed, tense courtroom listens to testimony from a government witness, FRANK, 50's, very matter-of-fact and truthful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: He first came to me in January.
{DIALOGUE}: That would've been nineteen eighty- seven.
{DIALOGUE}: He wanted to rent warehouse space along the harbor.
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't ask too many questions; I'm a businessman also.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FEDERAL COURTHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another witness, MRS. BERRY, 40's, pedantic on the stand --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BERRY
{DIALOGUE}: I told Mr. Ayala there were irregularities in his tax return.
{DIALOGUE}: And I couldn't represent him unless we could explain this...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FEDERAL COURTHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHEILA, 38, a mousy secretary, is on the stand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carlos sits at the defendant's table listening raptly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gordon and Castro sit in the back watching Helena who pays close attention to the witness --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHEILA
{DIALOGUE}: I was the company secretary from 1991 to 1994.
{DIALOGUE}: I supposedly worked for all six companies.
{DIALOGUE}: But... they weren't... I mean, it was just one empty office with a desk and a telephone.
{DIALOGUE}: We never sold anything the whole time I was there.
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes people came and got paid.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't really know what we did.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROSECUTOR
{DIALOGUE}: Did Mr. Ayala say where the money came from?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHEILA
{DIALOGUE}: No, and I didn't ask.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROSECUTOR
